  <h3><strong><a name="top" id="top">Searching the database: overview</a></strong></h3>
  <p>Query functionality includes defining a very specific query, using a customized 
    query, using saved queries and accessing specific issue ids. You can also 
    use the <em>Issue List </em> to access the last query.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Know issue number: Enter it in &quot;Issue ID&quot; field.</li>
    <li>Know attribute values for issue: use advanced query</li>
    <li>Know approximate information about issue: use custom query</li>
    <li>Already defined search parameters: use saved queries</li>
  </ul>
  <p>For ease of use, frequently used queries can be saved. Use the left navigation 
    link or the query bar to access saved queries. </p>
  <h4><a name="bar" id="bar">The Query bar</a></h4>
  <p>The query bar contains links to frequently used search functionality.</p>
  <ul>
    <li>If you have any saved queries, a drop down box will appear first on this 
      bar. Each of your saved queries appears in this box. You can select the 
      saved query you need and click the <strong>Go</strong> button.</li>
    <li>The <strong>Artifact Id</strong> form allows you to search the database for a specific 
      issue id.</li>
    <li>The <em>Advanced Query</em> link allows you to specify detailed search criteria.</li>
    <li>The <em>Custom Query</em> link is a text string search feature</li>
    <li>The <em>Issue List</em> link will run the last query or any saved query 
      you've set as a default</li>
  </ul>
  <h4><a name="issueid" id="issueid">Searching by Issue ID</a></h4>
  <p>To access a specific issue enter the issue number <bo>in</bo> the search 
    form and click the <strong>Artifact Id</strong> button. If the id you requested is not 
    found an error message will appear and you can enter a different id.</p>
  <p>Accessing issues across projects requires the following information:</p>
  <ul>
    <li> permission to view issues in the target project</li>
    <li> short name of the target project</li>
    <li> issue number</li>
  </ul>
  <p> For instance, jdoe is in the games (gam) project and wants to view an issue 
    from the interface (int) project. Jdoe can enter INT1 and click the <strong>Artifact 
    Id</strong> button to view the first issue in the Interface project.</p>
  <p>If you do not have permission to view issues in the target project you will 
    receive an error message. Likewise, if you enter an invalid project id or 
    issue number an error message will be generated.</p>
